Use map-struct. It can map one field to another from source to target object. avoids a lot of boiler plate code. works well with spring and you can inject them as normal beans. If you are good with generics you can play with it in n number of ways. You can read about it here https://www.tutorialspoint.com/mapstruct/index.htm
It is a very versatile mapping lib.

```
@Component
public interface MyMapper&lt;T extends Entity, K extends Pojo&gt; {


  K toPojo(T entity);

  T toEntity(K dto);

}

Impl:

@Component
@Mapper(componentModel = &quot;spring&quot;, uses = {AnotherMapper.class})
public abstract class EmployeeMapper implements MyMapper&lt;EmployeeEntity, EmployeePojo&gt; {

  @Autowired
  protected SomeLookupService someLookupService;


  @Mapping(source = &quot;dto.fullname&quot;, target = &quot;name&quot;)
  public abstract EmployeeEntity toEntity(EmployeePojo dto);


  @Mapping(source = &quot;entity.name&quot;, target = &quot;fullname&quot;)
  @Mapping(source = &quot;entity&quot;, target = &quot;additionalInfo&quot;, qualifiedByName = &quot;additionalInfo&quot;)
  public abstract EmployeePojo toPojo(EmployeeEntity entity);

  @Named(&quot;additionalInfo&quot;)
  protected String populateAdditionalInfo(Entity entity) {

    // your own logic to populate AdditionalInfo.java
  }
}

Note:
 
EmployeeEntity extends Entity
EmployeePojo extends Pojo
someLookupService -&gt; if you wanna inject some other component to do complex operations during mapping and modify content, for example populating some aggregations etc. Depends on how you would like to use.
AnotherMapper.class -&gt; a similar mapper if you have nested fields which are complex types.

```
You can inject this mapper straight into your service code.

